cff-version: 1.2.0
message: "If you use this software, please cite it."
title: "Memorised them All"
abstract: >-
  Local, token-free file-to-knowledge-graph memory MCP server and Claude plugin
  (Desktop and Code). Point it at files or folders; it converts them to Markdown
  entirely on-device — PDF, Word/Excel/PowerPoint (including legacy binary
  .doc/.ppt/.xls via optional LibreOffice), CSV, HTML, RTF, EPUB, plain text, and
  safely-unpacked archives — then builds a layered knowledge graph (entities,
  relations, themes), an exportable Markdown memory, and per-document notes.
  Version 2 is a deterministic, model-free re-architecture: no LLM, no Ollama, no
  GPU, no embedding/vision/audio models, just pure-Python rules, so a digest
  always completes (no model or network to fail) and produces byte-identical
  output for the same input. It is 100% local and private — no telemetry, no
  uploads, no API keys. Recall uses model-free, script-agnostic BM25 lexical
  ranking (Bengali-aware, with a low-confidence guard that declines off-topic
  queries) and returns a tiny cited slice; document contents are never returned
  to the model, so building or recalling whole folders costs near-zero Claude
  context tokens. Specialised handling includes legacy Bengali SutonnyMJ/Bijoy
  to-Unicode recovery (including the vetted reorder-artifact repair রম্ন→রু) and
  broken-font Bengali PDF re-OCR, optional image OCR (Tesseract), beneficiary-PII
  suppression, atomic crash-safe writes, and per-file conversion timeouts.
